Tripp's in the quench.

10:18.368 --> 10:21.621
<i>‐ Pull it out of the quench,</i>
<i>I see a small warp.</i>

10:21.621 --> 10:23.123
But I believe
I can grind it out.

10:23.123 --> 10:25.125
That will work just fine.

10:25.125 --> 10:26.459
<i>♪ ♪</i>

10:26.459 --> 10:28.795
‐ Now, I'm focused on trying
to shape the blade.

10:28.795 --> 10:31.381
I have to have
a clipped point on it,

10:31.381 --> 10:34.801
so I cut off
a piece of the edge

10:34.801 --> 10:35.969
and then I take it back

10:35.969 --> 10:38.638
and finish shaping
the blade from there.

10:38.638 --> 10:40.306
‐ The tip doesn't look
very right.

10:40.306 --> 10:41.474
‐ Not yet.

10:41.474 --> 10:42.559
<i>♪ ♪</i>

10:42.559 --> 10:44.561
<i>‐ I get my blade shaped</i>

10:44.561 --> 10:47.230
and now I'm thinking
about heat treating it.

10:47.230 --> 10:49.983
<i>♪ ♪</i>

10:49.983 --> 10:53.903
I take it out and it seems nice
and straight to me,

10:53.903 --> 10:55.905
so feeling pretty good.

10:57.240 --> 10:59.701
‐ Garrett's
adjusting his forge,

10:59.701 --> 11:01.327
so he's gonna get ready
to do the quench.

11:01.327 --> 11:04.873
‐ Because my mild steel
on the outside ends up perfect,

11:04.873 --> 11:06.666
I'm kind of anticipating
a warp.

11:06.666 --> 11:08.168
So I need to do
something about that.

11:08.168 --> 11:11.713
<i>♪ ♪</i>

11:11.713 --> 11:14.174
‐ He made a little three‐pin
straightening jig.

11:14.174 --> 11:15.258
That's not a bad idea.
‐ That's a good plan.

11:15.258 --> 11:16.718
‐ Yeah, that's a
really good idea.

11:16.718 --> 11:18.845
‐ You'd expect with the kind
of training military mindset

11:18.845 --> 11:20.680
is contingency plans.

11:20.680 --> 11:22.891
If this could happen,
I gotta be set for that.

11:22.891 --> 11:25.351
<i>‐ Even though I'm losing</i>
<i>minutes on the clock,</i>

11:25.351 --> 11:27.604
I know it's something that's
gonna help me in the end.

11:27.604 --> 11:29.856
<i>♪ ♪</i>

11:29.856 --> 11:31.691
‐ Garrett just quenched.

11:31.691 --> 11:34.277
‐ Pull it out, and I've got
just a little wiggle in it.

11:34.277 --> 11:38.031
<i>So I head over to my jig,</i>
<i>give it a good twist,</i>

11:38.031 --> 11:39.365
warp seems to come right out.

11:39.365 --> 11:40.867
‐ I think Garrett's
really showing some‐‐

11:40.867 --> 11:43.536
some really smart,
scientific work.

11:43.536 --> 11:46.122
<i>♪ ♪</i>

11:46.122 --> 11:48.249
‐ Rick over here
has just quenched.

11:48.249 --> 11:50.251
‐ Oh!
‐ That looks warped.

11:50.251 --> 11:52.420
‐ That looks like a big warp
in the spine, yeah.

11:52.420 --> 11:54.714
‐ No, no, no, no,
that ain't gonna work.

11:54.714 --> 11:56.216
That ain't gonna work at all.

11:56.216 --> 11:57.592
<i>I don't know</i>
<i>why the blade warped,</i>

11:57.592 --> 12:00.887
but I'm gonna do it again,
and hope for the best.

12:00.887 --> 12:02.305
<i>♪ ♪</i>

12:02.305 --> 12:04.224
‐ Man, that blade
was smokin' hot.

12:04.224 --> 12:06.309
‐ Yeah.
‐ Now that‐‐that's a big issue.

12:06.309 --> 12:08.061
‐ When it's that hot,
when you go for the quench,

12:08.061 --> 12:11.397
you run a bigger risk
of cracking, huge grain growth.

12:11.397 --> 12:13.399
That'll cause edge warping.

12:13.399 --> 12:15.193
‐ Damn!
It's even be worse.

12:15.193 --> 12:16.527
I can't believe
that this is happening.

12:16.527 --> 12:17.904
<i>I don't want</i>
<i>to be eliminated</i>

12:17.904 --> 12:20.073
solely because
my blade has a warp.

12:20.073 --> 12:21.491
This is horrible.

12:21.491 --> 12:22.575
<i>♪ ♪</i>

12:22.575 --> 12:24.494
All right,
we're going back again.

12:24.494 --> 12:26.079
‐ Rick is back in the fire.

12:26.079 --> 12:27.747
<i>‐ I only have 15 minutes left.</i>

12:27.747 --> 12:29.415
I'm on my third quench.

12:29.415 --> 12:31.417
I don't have time
to do it again.

12:31.417 --> 12:34.003
If this fails, I could
very well be going home.

12:34.003 --> 12:35.421
‐ Oh, my God.

12:35.421 --> 12:36.589
<i>♪ ♪</i>

12:40.009 --> 12:42.220
‐ That thing's
at welding temperature.

12:42.220 --> 12:44.264
Third time he's brought it up
to that temperature.

12:44.264 --> 12:46.641
Each time,
he's growing that grain.

12:46.641 --> 12:48.142
<i>♪ ♪</i>

12:48.142 --> 12:49.769
<i>‐ Third quench, warped again.</i>

12:49.769 --> 12:51.229
Oh, man.

12:51.229 --> 12:52.605
I can't get it straight.

12:52.605 --> 12:53.940
<i>♪ ♪</i>

12:53.940 --> 12:56.734
So, I decide to cut my losses,
clamp it in the vice

12:56.734 --> 12:59.779
and hope that that
straightens it somewhat.

12:59.779 --> 13:02.156
<i>[rock music]</i>

13:02.156 --> 13:03.992
‐ I go over
to clean up my blade

13:03.992 --> 13:07.287
and then I notice
a delamination popping out.

13:07.287 --> 13:08.955
Ah!

13:08.955 --> 13:11.708
So I started grinding it away,
and it gets bigger.

13:11.708 --> 13:13.751
<i>Then, I'm also noticing</i>

13:13.751 --> 13:15.628
that I have a warp
coming up in my blade.

13:15.628 --> 13:17.505
Son of a [bleep].

13:17.505 --> 13:18.715
I think I screwed up

13:18.715 --> 13:20.466
when I was over there
grinding or something.

13:20.466 --> 13:22.427
I started dipping it
in some water too early

13:22.427 --> 13:23.803
<i>and cooling her down.</i>

13:23.803 --> 13:26.139
Maybe that's where I ended up
picking up the warp.

13:26.139 --> 13:29.434
I do not have time to fix
the big issues that I have,

13:29.434 --> 13:31.853
but I do have a few minutes
left on the clock,

13:31.853 --> 13:34.480
so I'm thinking maybe I can put
some serrated edges in

13:34.480 --> 13:36.232
that'll catch
the judges' eyes.

13:36.232 --> 13:37.483
‐ There's no requirement

13:37.483 --> 13:40.194
for any kind of serrated back
to this blade.

13:40.194 --> 13:42.780
‐ Take it to the limit.
Go above and beyond.

13:42.780 --> 13:45.491
‐ Even though I have
a couple of issues,

13:45.491 --> 13:49.412
maybe they'll give me points
for something.

13:49.412 --> 13:51.748
<i>♪ ♪</i>

13:51.748 --> 13:54.542
<i>‐ I see Gene putting</i>
<i>serrations in his blade.</i>

13:54.542 --> 13:56.961
<i>I've got</i>
<i>a couple minutes left.</i>

13:56.961 --> 13:58.421
If I get these serrations
in here,

13:58.421 --> 13:59.839
this thing's gonna look badass,

13:59.839 --> 14:01.883
and this gonna set me above
the rest of the marines.

14:01.883 --> 14:03.217
<i>♪ ♪</i>

14:03.217 --> 14:05.595
‐ 20 seconds!
‐ [bleep]!

14:05.595 --> 14:07.096
I don't even have
the serrations

14:07.096 --> 14:08.765
on the other side of the blade.

14:08.765 --> 14:11.142
Now, I'm nervous.
Now, I'm scrambling.

14:11.142 --> 14:15.772
‐ Five, four, three, two, one.

14:15.772 --> 14:18.608
Bladesmiths, shut down
your machines, drop your tools.

14:18.608 --> 14:21.319
This first round
of competition is over.

14:21.319 --> 14:23.237
‐ Whoo!
‐ Good job, good job.

14:23.237 --> 14:24.572
‐ Wow.

14:24.572 --> 14:27.158
<i>Holy cow.</i>
<i>That was insanely tough.</i>

14:27.158 --> 14:30.536
It's not looking good.
I'm in a bad spot.

14:30.536 --> 14:33.456
<i>♪ ♪</i>

14:33.456 --> 14:35.541
‐ Bladesmiths, in this first
round of competition,

14:35.541 --> 14:38.753
we asked you to pay tribute
to a weapon made iconic

14:38.753 --> 14:40.338
by the United States
Marine Corps,

14:40.338 --> 14:41.714
the Ka‐Bar.

14:41.714 --> 14:44.050
Now, it's time for the judges
to see how you did.

14:44.050 --> 14:45.343
Tripp, you're up first.

14:45.343 --> 14:47.386
Please present your blade
to the judges.

14:47.386 --> 14:49.222
<i>♪ ♪</i>

14:49.222 --> 14:50.848
<i>‐ Looks really solid.</i>

14:50.848 --> 14:52.809
<i>It looks like</i>
<i>one piece of steel.</i>

14:52.809 --> 14:54.310
Your file work
on the back is nice

14:54.310 --> 14:56.145
'cause it's all radiused.

14:56.145 --> 14:58.940
It's got a teeny bit
of a warp to it,

14:58.940 --> 15:03.361
but what I see here is
a nice, lean, light,

15:03.361 --> 15:05.363
solid piece of steel.
Good job.

15:05.363 --> 15:07.657
‐ Thank you, David.
‐ Rick, you're up.

15:07.657 --> 15:09.659
Please present your blade
to the judges.

15:09.659 --> 15:11.744
<i>♪ ♪</i>

15:11.744 --> 15:14.038
<i>‐ Well, Rick.</i>
<i>There's a couple issues.</i>

15:14.038 --> 15:16.791
<i>What I always fear about</i>
<i>a thin edge has happened.</i>

15:16.791 --> 15:18.709
It wanders all over.

15:18.709 --> 15:21.462
It's enough that in order
to split the difference

15:21.462 --> 15:22.880
and grind a straight line
in there,

15:22.880 --> 15:25.216
you're probably gonna lose
1/8 to 1/4 of an inch

15:25.216 --> 15:27.635
of height on your blade here.

15:27.635 --> 15:29.428
Also on the spine,

15:29.428 --> 15:31.389
<i>there's a seam</i>

15:31.389 --> 15:34.475
that's most likely the result
of quenching

15:34.475 --> 15:37.687
from really hot temperatures
and multiple times.

15:37.687 --> 15:40.231
I like your clip,
it's got a nice radius to it

15:40.231 --> 15:42.108
and the weight is good.

15:42.108 --> 15:44.610
But, you can't escape
this crack up here

15:44.610 --> 15:47.822
and that edge is really
meandering all over the place.

15:47.822 --> 15:49.699
<i>♪ ♪</i>

15:49.699 --> 15:50.825
‐ Gene, you're up next.

15:50.825 --> 15:53.161
Please present your steel
to the judges.

15:53.161 --> 15:54.829
<i>♪ ♪</i>

15:54.829 --> 15:57.832
<i>‐ Biggest thing is dealing</i>
<i>with that warp.</i>

15:57.832 --> 16:00.084
<i>I like the profile,</i>
<i>don't like the clip.</i>

16:00.084 --> 16:03.880
That Ka‐Bar has that clip
that goes down to the point.

16:03.880 --> 16:07.884
Love to see that because I like
the rest of this profile.

16:07.884 --> 16:09.844
You know, when doing a San Mai,
a lot of people think

16:09.844 --> 16:12.555
that just putting a little bit
on the blade is a good idea.

16:12.555 --> 16:15.516
That blister is right
where that material ends.

16:15.516 --> 16:16.726
That's pretty deep.

16:16.726 --> 16:18.144
[blade clicking]

16:18.144 --> 16:20.605
This is something that
really needs to be dealt with,

16:20.605 --> 16:22.148
so if you move forward,

16:22.148 --> 16:24.650
we'd really like
to see you take care of that.

16:24.650 --> 16:26.402
‐ Thank you, Dave.
‐ Garrett, you're up.

16:26.402 --> 16:28.321
Please present your blade
to the judges.

16:28.321 --> 16:30.031
<i>♪ ♪</i>

16:30.031 --> 16:32.825
<i>‐ All right, Garrett, this is</i>
<i>what I like about your blade.</i>

16:32.825 --> 16:34.285
<i>It's aggressive.</i>

16:34.285 --> 16:36.913
One slice with it,
it's got a good weight to it,

16:36.913 --> 16:40.041
thick spine, you can really see
what San Mai does

16:40.041 --> 16:43.127
when you have mild steel
marry up with hardenable steel.

16:43.127 --> 16:45.463
Looks like solid, clean work.
Good job.

16:45.463 --> 16:47.256
‐ Thank you.

16:47.256 --> 16:48.716
‐ All right, gentlemen.

16:48.716 --> 16:50.593
The judges' deliberation
is complete.

16:50.593 --> 16:52.720
The bladesmith leaving
The Forge is...

16:52.720 --> 16:56.891
<i>♪ ♪</i>

16:56.891 --> 16:59.685
Rick, your blade
didn't make the cut.

16:59.685 --> 17:02.063
‐ Rick, you brought us a knife
with a great profile,

17:02.063 --> 17:04.899
but it also had a wobbly edge,
and worst of all,

17:04.899 --> 17:07.985
that split through
that W1 right in the middle,

17:07.985 --> 17:09.362
and that's why
we're sending you home.

17:09.362 --> 17:10.821
‐ I understand.

17:10.821 --> 17:12.740
‐ I have to ask you
to please surrender your blade.

17:12.740 --> 17:14.784
<i>♪ ♪</i>

17:14.784 --> 17:16.869
<i>‐ There were many things</i>
<i>that I was chasing,</i>

17:16.869 --> 17:19.121
and unfortunately,
the clock just ran out

17:19.121 --> 17:21.916
before I had the chance
to correct some of those.

17:21.916 --> 17:24.752
My advice to the other smiths:
keep what you're doing,

17:24.752 --> 17:26.754
and kick the other
branches' asses.

17:26.754 --> 17:29.423
<i>♪ ♪</i>

17:29.423 --> 17:30.883
‐ Bladesmiths, congratulations.

17:30.883 --> 17:33.427
You've made it to the second
round of this competition,

17:33.427 --> 17:34.971
and now that those blades
have been tempered,

17:34.971 --> 17:36.430
it's time to make them
fully functional

17:36.430 --> 17:38.099
by attaching handles to them.

17:38.099 --> 17:40.434
<i>Your handles must include</i>
<i>a symmetrical crossguard,</i>

17:40.434 --> 17:44.689
<i>stacked leather handle,</i>
<i>and a butt cap, or pommel.</i>

17:44.689 --> 17:46.107
Make sure you do
your best work,

17:46.107 --> 17:47.441
address the flaws and issues

17:47.441 --> 17:48.901
that were identified
in your blades

17:48.901 --> 17:50.570
because after your blades
have been tested,

17:50.570 --> 17:52.822
one of you will be asked
to surrender your Ka‐Bar

17:52.822 --> 17:54.782
and leave The Forge.

17:54.782 --> 17:57.660
Good luck, gents.
Your two hours starts now.

17:57.660 --> 17:59.829
‐ This is the first time I have
to make a stack handle,

17:59.829 --> 18:01.581
and I've only got
two hours to do it.

18:01.581 --> 18:02.957
It seems like there's no way

18:02.957 --> 18:05.084
I'm gonna be able
to get it done in that time.

18:05.084 --> 18:07.295
Right now, I'm trying to make
three or four pieces

18:07.295 --> 18:09.338
and then glue those together
to make a full stack

18:09.338 --> 18:10.881
instead of trying to do it
all at once.

18:10.881 --> 18:12.383
<i>As I'm gluing 'em up,</i>

18:12.383 --> 18:14.135
<i>the pieces of leather are</i>
<i>slipping all over the place.</i>

18:14.135 --> 18:16.137
<i>They're not staying exactly</i>
<i>where I want 'em to be.</i>

18:16.137 --> 18:18.139
See, like that's coming apart
right there.

18:18.139 --> 18:19.890
‐ If you want the compression
of the leather

18:19.890 --> 18:21.183
to work with you,

18:21.183 --> 18:23.019
then it's better to glue
as you're compressing

18:23.019 --> 18:25.313
versus glue it,
let it get hard,

18:25.313 --> 18:26.981
and then try to compress it.

18:26.981 --> 18:28.190
‐ It's a lot more stressful

18:28.190 --> 18:29.650
than I thought
it was ever gonna be.

18:29.650 --> 18:30.985
<i>♪ ♪</i>

18:30.985 --> 18:31.986
<i>‐ The judges</i>
<i>have made it clear</i>

18:31.986 --> 18:33.279
<i>I gotta get rid of that warp.</i>

18:33.279 --> 18:35.197
<i>I'm taking two pieces</i>
<i>of angle iron,</i>

18:35.197 --> 18:36.490
<i>lay 'em on the table,</i>

18:36.490 --> 18:38.784
<i>and then put a piece</i>
<i>of flat metal on top.</i>

18:38.784 --> 18:40.870
‐ He's doing it a smart way
with that block.

18:40.870 --> 18:43.497
He will get, you know, pressure
distributed across the blade

18:43.497 --> 18:45.708
as opposed to being
just in that one point.

18:45.708 --> 18:47.627
‐ [laughs]

18:47.627 --> 18:49.712
It's straight!

18:49.712 --> 18:51.881
<i>I got to address</i>
<i>this delamination</i>

18:51.881 --> 18:53.215
<i>because it's ugly.</i>

18:53.215 --> 18:56.052
<i>I'm gonna go with the epoxy</i>
<i>and 1095 steel.</i>

18:56.052 --> 18:57.511
<i>It's a quick, fast, easy fix.</i>

18:57.511 --> 18:58.929
‐ This is what I like about it:

18:58.929 --> 19:02.642
you're filling in a crater
that could be a weak spot.

19:02.642 --> 19:04.268
Sometimes when
you grind it away,

19:04.268 --> 19:06.145
the danger of that
is you weaken the spot.

19:06.145 --> 19:08.939
If you try to weld it,
the heat can change

19:08.939 --> 19:10.816
the construction
of that whole metal.

19:10.816 --> 19:12.860
So, maybe this Bondo's
not such a bad idea at all.

19:12.860 --> 19:16.030
‐ How's it going, man?
‐ I haven't broke it yet.

19:16.030 --> 19:17.239
‐ Hey, that's a plus.

19:17.239 --> 19:18.532
<i>♪ ♪</i>

19:18.532 --> 19:20.076
<i>‐ So, I want to do</i>
<i>a brass guard.</i>

19:20.076 --> 19:23.287
Right, it's the softest,
so easiest to maneuver.

19:23.287 --> 19:24.997
‐ Although the original has
a steel guard,

19:24.997 --> 19:26.540
brass is so much easier
to work.

19:26.540 --> 19:29.377
It's a great choice for
a material in this competition.

19:29.377 --> 19:31.170
‐ 60 minutes, bladesmiths.

19:31.170 --> 19:34.048
You have 60 minutes remaining
to finish your blades.

19:34.048 --> 19:35.424
<i>♪ ♪</i>

19:35.424 --> 19:37.426
<i>‐ So, I want this to be</i>
<i>a traditional Ka‐Bar,</i>

19:37.426 --> 19:39.887
<i>so I used mild steel</i>
<i>for the guard and the pommel.</i>

19:39.887 --> 19:41.222
<i>♪ ♪</i>

19:41.222 --> 19:42.848
What the [bleep].

19:42.848 --> 19:45.476
It's really frustrating trying
to drill just a couple holes.

19:45.476 --> 19:46.852
[drill head scratches]
[bleep]!

19:46.852 --> 19:48.187
This is taking a long time

19:48.187 --> 19:49.772
when I don't have
that much time.

19:49.772 --> 19:51.190
<i>♪ ♪</i>

19:51.190 --> 19:53.442
<i>‐ I'm gonna clamp a vice grip</i>
<i>on top of the tang</i>

19:53.442 --> 19:56.112
and drive it down
to compress all of it together.

19:56.112 --> 19:58.531
<i>You have to compress them</i>
<i>or there's gonna be gaps.</i>

19:58.531 --> 20:00.408
♪ ♪

20:00.408 --> 20:02.118
‐ Knock it down,
it locks into place.

20:02.118 --> 20:04.203
Keeps it until it dries.
‐ That's a great idea, man.

20:04.203 --> 20:06.288
‐ Hey, man, that's a good idea!
‐ Yeah.

20:06.288 --> 20:07.832
<i>♪ ♪</i>

20:07.832 --> 20:09.166
<i>‐ So, I get my guard ready.</i>

20:09.166 --> 20:10.918
<i>Now, I have to attach it</i>
<i>to the blade.</i>

20:10.918 --> 20:12.545
I don't wanna weld it
because it's brass.

20:12.545 --> 20:13.879
<i>When you're playing</i>
<i>with a soft steel,</i>

20:13.879 --> 20:15.339
<i>I think the welder</i>
<i>would obliterate it.</i>

20:15.339 --> 20:17.299
<i>‐ Looks like Gene's gonna</i>
<i>solder his guard in place.</i>

20:17.299 --> 20:18.551
‐ Awesome.
‐ Not a bad idea.

20:18.551 --> 20:20.136
‐ You know,
with a stacked leather handle,

20:20.136 --> 20:21.929
there can be some movement
in that leather.

20:21.929 --> 20:23.931
Having that soldered
is a good idea.

20:23.931 --> 20:25.015
<i>♪ ♪</i>

20:25.015 --> 20:27.184
‐ Damn it!
My solder didn't work.

20:27.184 --> 20:30.354
<i>At home, I would fix this,</i>
<i>but here you have to move on</i>

20:30.354 --> 20:32.064
<i>'cause you got</i>
<i>that clock going.</i>

20:32.064 --> 20:34.942
<i>I'm worried that guard's gonna</i>
<i>be loose in Ben Abbott's hands</i>

20:34.942 --> 20:37.111
and he's gonna tear me up.

20:37.111 --> 20:38.821
‐ Bladesmiths, you only have

20:38.821 --> 20:40.823
30 minutes remaining
in this round.

20:40.823 --> 20:42.199
<i>♪ ♪</i>

20:42.199 --> 20:44.535
<i>‐ I've got some rebar</i>
<i>on the end of my tang,</i>

20:44.535 --> 20:46.746
<i>I've gotta peen it over</i>
<i>on the pommel.</i>

20:46.746 --> 20:48.622
This is
the mechanical connection

20:48.622 --> 20:51.083
that's gonna hold
the entire handle on the blade.

20:51.083 --> 20:52.293
Nope!

20:52.293 --> 20:54.003
‐ That's a lot of tang
sticking up.

20:54.003 --> 20:55.796
‐ People
very often miscalculate

20:55.796 --> 20:58.382
how much
rivet head you need to peen.

20:58.382 --> 21:00.134
‐ It's just not moving at all.

21:00.134 --> 21:02.344
<i>♪ ♪</i>

21:02.344 --> 21:05.097
Now, it's just hot as [bleep].
All for nothing.

21:05.097 --> 21:08.309
Peening this blade is make or
break for my blade right now.

21:08.309 --> 21:09.643
<i>If I don't get this fixed,</i>

21:09.643 --> 21:12.146
<i>worst‐case scenario,</i>
<i>the pommel pops off</i>

21:12.146 --> 21:13.689
and my whole handle
comes apart.

21:13.689 --> 21:14.982
<i>That would definitely</i>
<i>send me home.</i>

21:19.236 --> 21:20.905
<i>‐ So, I'm moving on</i>
<i>to the pommel next.</i>

21:20.905 --> 21:22.406
I go over to drill my hole

21:22.406 --> 21:24.492
<i>so it'll fit over</i>
<i>the very end of my tang,</i>

21:24.492 --> 21:26.243
and that drill bit
is bouncing off.

21:26.243 --> 21:28.454
<i>♪ ♪</i>

21:29.705 --> 21:31.582
[grunts]

21:31.582 --> 21:33.959
<i>♪ ♪</i>

21:33.959 --> 21:35.753
I reach into my go bag
and pull out a Band‐Aid

21:35.753 --> 21:37.421
and slap it on and keep going.

21:37.421 --> 21:38.756
‐ Like a marine, always ready.

21:38.756 --> 21:40.466
Brought his own Band‐Aid.
[laughter]

21:40.466 --> 21:41.801
‐ Gene brought his own
Band‐Aids.

21:41.801 --> 21:43.260
I love it.

21:43.260 --> 21:45.262
<i>‐ I got everything I need</i>
<i>in my go bag.</i>

21:45.262 --> 21:46.639
<i>I got stuff for land nav,</i>

21:46.639 --> 21:48.808
<i>I got stuff for night lights.</i>

21:48.808 --> 21:50.851
You know,
whistle in case I get lost.

21:50.851 --> 21:52.144
<i>♪ ♪</i>

21:52.144 --> 21:54.230
I got my matches.

21:54.230 --> 21:55.606
<i>I come prepared.</i>

21:55.606 --> 21:58.150
‐ Ten minutes, bladesmiths!

21:58.150 --> 22:00.653
‐ I've noticed on the Ka‐Bar
at the table at the front,

22:00.653 --> 22:01.987
this Ka‐Bar has ribs,

22:01.987 --> 22:03.781
and most of the Marine Corps
Ka‐Bars have ribs.

22:03.781 --> 22:05.658
<i>But I've got one more</i>
<i>little trick up my sleeve,</i>

22:05.658 --> 22:07.576
<i>just to try to set me</i>
<i>above the rest.</i>

22:07.576 --> 22:09.829
‐ That's really
a cool attention to detail

22:09.829 --> 22:11.664
to put those grooves
in the handle.

22:11.664 --> 22:15.000
<i>‐ The grooves in the handle</i>
<i>do help grip it more.</i>

22:15.000 --> 22:16.377
Hopefully the judges like it.

22:16.377 --> 22:18.420
‐ Five, four,

22:18.420 --> 22:21.674
three, two, one.

22:21.674 --> 22:23.092
Bladesmiths,
shut down your machines.

22:23.092 --> 22:25.511
This second round of
competition is over.

22:25.511 --> 22:27.471
Good job.
‐ Oh, good job.

22:27.471 --> 22:28.639
It's an ugly baby.

22:28.639 --> 22:30.933
It‐‐it‐‐ugh.
Not proud of it.

22:30.933 --> 22:32.017
<i>But at the same time,</i>

22:32.017 --> 22:33.561
<i>I feel like I did</i>
<i>the best I could</i>

22:33.561 --> 22:35.020
in that amount of time
that I had.

22:35.020 --> 22:36.355
[exhales deeply]

22:36.355 --> 22:39.233
‐ Marines,
welcome to the rifle chop.

22:39.233 --> 22:41.318
To test the strength
and durability of your blades

22:41.318 --> 22:43.487
as well as the overall
construction of your Ka‐Bars,

22:43.487 --> 22:45.865
I will be chopping mercilessly
into these rifles.

22:45.865 --> 22:47.324
<i>♪ ♪</i>

22:47.324 --> 22:48.701
Tripp, you're up first.
You ready?

22:48.701 --> 22:50.202
‐ Have at it, killer.
‐ [clicks tongue]

22:50.202 --> 22:51.996
All right.

22:51.996 --> 22:53.873
<i>‐ This Ka‐Bar,</i>
<i>it looks badass,</i>

22:53.873 --> 22:55.374
<i>but, hey,</i>
<i>there could be</i>

22:55.374 --> 22:56.709
<i>a fracture or something</i>
<i>in my blade.</i>

22:56.709 --> 22:58.711
<i>That thing could pop,</i>
<i>go across the shop,</i>

22:58.711 --> 22:59.837
<i>and kill somebody.</i>

22:59.837 --> 23:06.760
<i>♪ ♪</i>

23:12.349 --> 23:14.184
‐ [chuckles]
Holy crap.

23:14.184 --> 23:15.895
<i>♪ ♪</i>

23:15.895 --> 23:18.063
‐ Well, Tripp, nice job.

23:18.063 --> 23:21.108
There is glinting here

23:21.108 --> 23:22.610
and up here towards the tip,

23:22.610 --> 23:24.904
but this held up
phenomenally well.

23:24.904 --> 23:27.114
‐ Oorah, thank you.
‐ All right, Gene, you're up.

23:27.114 --> 23:28.866
You ready?
‐ Giddy up.

23:28.866 --> 23:29.909
‐ All right.

23:29.909 --> 23:31.368
<i>♪ ♪</i>

23:31.368 --> 23:33.662
<i>‐ Just the way he swings</i>
<i>that thing into that rifle,</i>

23:33.662 --> 23:34.914
<i>it's insane.</i>

23:34.914 --> 23:36.624
<i>No knife should be able</i>
<i>to handle that,</i>

23:36.624 --> 23:39.877
<i>and I can't believe that</i>
<i>he's gonna do it to mine.</i>

23:39.877 --> 23:44.548
<i>♪ ♪</i>

23:44.548 --> 23:45.716
‐ Ooh!

23:45.716 --> 23:47.384
<i>♪ ♪</i>

23:47.384 --> 23:48.886
‐ Ah!
‐ Nice!

23:48.886 --> 23:53.641
<i>♪ ♪</i>

23:53.641 --> 23:55.434
Heck yeah.
‐ Hoo‐wee!

23:55.434 --> 23:56.602
[clanking]

23:56.602 --> 23:57.770
‐ Hear that sound?
‐ Yep.

23:57.770 --> 23:58.979
‐ That's your guard.
‐ Yep.

23:58.979 --> 24:00.439
‐ Your guard is now loose.

24:00.439 --> 24:02.691
Can't tell if the handle
slipped back from it,

24:02.691 --> 24:05.027
but there's a big gap
there in this motion.

24:05.027 --> 24:08.113
Overall, though, it's all
in one piece, so well done.

24:08.113 --> 24:09.406
‐ Thank you.

24:09.406 --> 24:11.116
‐ Well, Garrett, you've seen
what I'm gonna do.

24:11.116 --> 24:12.409
‐ Oh, God.

24:12.409 --> 24:13.786
‐ How you feeling?

24:13.786 --> 24:15.287
‐ Yup.
‐ [laughs]

24:15.287 --> 24:17.247
All right.
Yup it is.

24:17.247 --> 24:18.958
<i>♪ ♪</i>

24:18.958 --> 24:20.501
<i>‐ This test is gonna be</i>

24:20.501 --> 24:21.961
<i>the hardest test</i>
<i>I've ever done</i>

24:21.961 --> 24:23.671
<i>on any of my blades.</i>

24:23.671 --> 24:26.090
<i>I'm afraid that that pommel</i>
<i>is just gonna come right off</i>

24:26.090 --> 24:27.925
and that's what's gonna
send me home.

24:27.925 --> 24:33.764
<i>♪ ♪</i>

24:33.764 --> 24:34.974
‐ Hoo‐ooh!

24:34.974 --> 24:39.144
<i>♪ ♪</i>

24:39.144 --> 24:40.479
‐ Was I the only one
that seen a spark?

24:40.479 --> 24:41.772
‐ That was crazy.

24:41.772 --> 24:43.148
‐ Well, Garrett,
there's a decent chunk

24:43.148 --> 24:44.525
out of your blade right here.

24:44.525 --> 24:47.486
<i>This is the site</i>
<i>of two impacts at least,</i>

24:47.486 --> 24:49.071
and it lost.
[chuckles]

24:49.071 --> 24:51.323
You know, yo‐‐there's
a piece of your blade still

24:51.323 --> 24:52.992
over there somewhere.

24:52.992 --> 24:55.327
The rest of your knife
is still tight, still there.

24:55.327 --> 24:57.329
It's all in one piece, mostly.

24:57.329 --> 24:58.497
‐ Thank you.

24:58.497 --> 25:00.290
‐ Up next is
the sharpness test,

25:00.290 --> 25:01.792
and for that,
I give you to Doug.

25:01.792 --> 25:03.585
‐ Oorah.
‐ [laughs]

25:03.585 --> 25:04.962
‐ Yes.

25:04.962 --> 25:07.840
All right, marines,
this is the sharpness test.

25:07.840 --> 25:09.341
<i>♪ ♪</i>

25:09.341 --> 25:12.052
Today, the fight is all about
cutting through these ropes.

25:12.052 --> 25:13.429
Tripp, you're up first.
You ready for this?

25:13.429 --> 25:15.014
‐ Oorah.
‐ Let's do it.

25:15.014 --> 25:22.021
<i>♪ ♪</i>

25:23.188 --> 25:26.150
[grunting]

25:31.864 --> 25:33.574
<i>‐ So I feel like, man,</i>

25:33.574 --> 25:34.825
<i>I was on top of the world</i>
<i>a while ago</i>

25:34.825 --> 25:36.452
and now I'm at the damn bottom
of the barrel

25:36.452 --> 25:38.037
<i>hoping not to go home.</i>

25:38.037 --> 25:40.414
‐ All right, Tripp,
I love the handle.

25:40.414 --> 25:43.709
It really marries into my hand
when I put it on,

25:43.709 --> 25:45.294
but the fact
that I can do this,

25:45.294 --> 25:47.379
it's not very sharp at all.

25:47.379 --> 25:49.631
‐ It did scratch
and cut a little bit,

25:49.631 --> 25:53.093
but not as deeply
as I thought it should.

25:53.093 --> 25:55.429
Overall, sir, your blade...

25:55.429 --> 25:56.555
<i>♪ ♪</i>

25:56.555 --> 25:57.890
Kinda cuts.

25:57.890 --> 25:59.516
‐ [laughs]

25:59.516 --> 26:00.601
‐ All right, Gene,
your turn, sir.

26:00.601 --> 26:01.977
You ready?
‐ You bet.

26:01.977 --> 26:03.353
‐ Let's do this.

26:03.353 --> 26:04.688
<i>♪ ♪</i>

26:04.688 --> 26:06.190
‐ [sighs]

26:06.190 --> 26:08.400
<i>♪ ♪</i>

26:08.400 --> 26:10.027
[exhales]

26:10.027 --> 26:12.613
‐ [grunting]

26:12.613 --> 26:15.240
<i>♪ ♪</i>

26:15.240 --> 26:17.367
‐ Giddy up.
[laughs]

26:17.367 --> 26:19.578
‐ Nice.
[chuckles]

26:19.578 --> 26:21.121
‐ All right, Gene, let's talk
about your Ka‐Bar here.

26:21.121 --> 26:22.247
The edge you put on,

26:22.247 --> 26:23.957
despite having some glinting
right here,

26:23.957 --> 26:25.250
is still sharp.

26:25.250 --> 26:26.919
Took down all the ropes.

26:26.919 --> 26:28.587
It feels good
when you're swinging it,

26:28.587 --> 26:30.631
and overall, sir, it will cut.

26:30.631 --> 26:31.882
‐ Yes.
‐ There he is.

26:31.882 --> 26:32.883
‐ He said it!
[chuckles]

26:32.883 --> 26:33.926
‐ All right, Garrett,
you're up next.

26:33.926 --> 26:36.178
You ready, sir?
both: Let's do it.

26:36.178 --> 26:38.764
<i>‐ I feel like I'm</i>
<i>at a definite disadvantage.</i>

26:38.764 --> 26:40.933
After Tripp's knife didn't
go through any of the ropes,

26:40.933 --> 26:42.768
<i>I need my knife</i>
<i>to cut through 'em,</i>

26:42.768 --> 26:44.269
<i>or else I could be going home.</i>

26:44.269 --> 26:51.276
<i>♪ ♪</i>

26:55.114 --> 26:57.157
‐ Man, oh man.
‐ All right, Garrett.

26:57.157 --> 26:58.659
The handle's a little bit
on the larger side,

26:58.659 --> 27:00.410
there's some extra space
right there.

27:00.410 --> 27:03.122
But when you grab onto it,
it is comfortable.

27:03.122 --> 27:05.541
Despite having a chip
right here,

27:05.541 --> 27:07.417
you can see it still cuts.

27:07.417 --> 27:09.419
On one of the swings,
it actually got hung up

27:09.419 --> 27:11.004
on that one section
right there,

27:11.004 --> 27:13.757
but it does cut through
the first rope,

27:13.757 --> 27:16.468
and some of the second rope,
and a little bit on the third.

27:16.468 --> 27:18.470
Overall, sir, it will cut.

27:18.470 --> 27:19.721
‐ Thank you.

27:19.721 --> 27:21.098
‐ All right, bladesmiths,

27:21.098 --> 27:22.975
the judges have made
their final decision.

27:22.975 --> 27:25.811
It's time for one of you marines
to leave The Forge.

27:25.811 --> 27:27.604
The bladesmith leaving
The Forge is...

27:27.604 --> 27:29.273
<i>♪ ♪</i>

27:32.901 --> 27:34.319
Garrett.

27:34.319 --> 27:35.821
Your blade didn't make the cut.

27:35.821 --> 27:37.990
‐ Garrett, above all else,
the quality of a blade

27:37.990 --> 27:40.158
is something
an end user depends on.

27:40.158 --> 27:41.660
While this was very close,

27:41.660 --> 27:43.328
we based our decision

27:43.328 --> 27:45.998
that your blade took the most
damage on the strength test.

27:45.998 --> 27:47.416
For that reason,
we're sending you home.

27:47.416 --> 27:48.625
‐ I understand.

27:48.625 --> 27:50.919
‐ Garrett,
please surrender your blade.

27:50.919 --> 27:53.338
<i>‐ My blade took</i>
<i>the most damage.</i>

27:53.338 --> 27:55.507
It's only fair that I go home.

27:55.507 --> 27:58.302
<i>But I'm so glad that I had</i>
<i>the opportunity to compete</i>

27:58.302 --> 28:00.804
<i>and especially</i>
<i>with three other marines.</i>

28:00.804 --> 28:02.389
<i>Talk about a brotherhood.</i>

28:02.389 --> 28:04.349
I would've loved to represent
the Marine Corps

28:04.349 --> 28:05.601
<i>in the final challenge,</i>

28:05.601 --> 28:07.352
<i>but you got two great smiths</i>
<i>out there</i>

28:07.352 --> 28:08.645
that are gonna do a great job.

28:08.645 --> 28:12.691
<i>♪ ♪</i>

28:12.691 --> 28:15.444
‐ Tripp, Gene, congratulations.
You fellas have made it

28:15.444 --> 28:17.446
to the next evolution
of this competition,

28:17.446 --> 28:19.364
which means
that you're one step closer

28:19.364 --> 28:22.034
to occupying the United States
Marine Corps' anvil

28:22.034 --> 28:24.828
at our final Battle
of the Branches competition.

28:24.828 --> 28:26.663
Now we're sending you back
to your home forges

28:26.663 --> 28:28.665
to recreate this.

28:28.665 --> 28:30.542
<i>♪ ♪</i>

28:30.542 --> 28:33.378
‐ Dang!
[both laugh]

28:33.378 --> 28:35.505
‐ Your final challenge
is to forge

28:35.505 --> 28:37.424
a Marine Corps officer sword,

28:37.424 --> 28:39.343
also known as a Mameluke.

28:39.343 --> 28:40.719
<i>♪ ♪</i>

28:40.719 --> 28:43.347
<i>Since 1825, the Mameluke sword</i>
<i>has been awarded</i>

28:43.347 --> 28:46.391
<i>to U. S. marines to recognize</i>
<i>extraordinary service.</i>

28:46.391 --> 28:47.768
<i>This tradition began</i>

28:47.768 --> 28:49.561
<i>when the rulers of Tripoli</i>
<i>bestowed this weapon</i>

28:49.561 --> 28:51.396
<i>upon Marine</i>
<i>Lieutenant Presley O'Bannon</i>

28:51.396 --> 28:54.232
<i>for his bravery</i>
<i>during the Battle of Derna.</i>

28:54.232 --> 28:55.400
<i>The weapon itself originates</i>

28:55.400 --> 28:57.402
<i>from the Ottoman Empire</i>
<i>in Persia,</i>

28:57.402 --> 28:59.905
<i>with many similarities</i>
<i>to the Persian shamshir.</i>

28:59.905 --> 29:01.907
<i>Featuring a thin blade,</i>
<i>shallow curve,</i>

29:01.907 --> 29:04.201
<i>and its signature</i>
<i>inward‐curved pommel,</i>

29:04.201 --> 29:07.704
<i>this deadly sword was ideal</i>
<i>for cavalry and foot soldiers</i>

29:07.704 --> 29:11.249
<i>to deliver lethal slashes</i>
<i>and thrusts on their enemy.</i>

29:11.249 --> 29:12.876
<i>This blade was so dangerous,</i>

29:12.876 --> 29:15.087
<i>legend had it that</i>
<i>it was nearly unbreakable</i>

29:15.087 --> 29:17.756
<i>and could cut a person in two.</i>

29:17.756 --> 29:19.967
The blade parameters
are as follows:

29:19.967 --> 29:23.053
the blade must be between
29 and 30 inches in length,

29:23.053 --> 29:27.099
the depth of the curve
must be between 3/4 and 1 inch,

29:27.099 --> 29:28.767
you must have
a curved handle head,

29:28.767 --> 29:30.936
a crossguard between
5 and 6 inches,

29:30.936 --> 29:33.397
and langets on both sides
of the blade.

29:33.397 --> 29:35.273
<i>‐ The gears are turning</i>
<i>in my brain already,</i>

29:35.273 --> 29:36.733
trying to figure out
how in the hell

29:36.733 --> 29:38.568
I'm getting ready
to put this thing together.

29:38.568 --> 29:40.112
‐ You'll have four days
at your home forges

29:40.112 --> 29:41.405
in which to complete
this challenge,

29:41.405 --> 29:42.614
and at the end
of those four days,

29:42.614 --> 29:44.783
you'll return
and present your swords

29:44.783 --> 29:46.535
to our panel of expert judges.

29:46.535 --> 29:48.203
And after they've thoroughly
tested them,

29:48.203 --> 29:51.456
they'll move one of you forward
to represent the Marine Corps

29:51.456 --> 29:53.959
at the Battle of the Branches
final competition

29:53.959 --> 29:56.169
and give you that opportunity

29:56.169 --> 29:59.172
to win a check for 50 grand.

29:59.172 --> 30:00.298
Good luck, bladesmiths.

30:00.298 --> 30:02.134
We'll see you in four days.

30:02.134 --> 30:03.427
‐ Oorah.
‐ Oorah.

30:03.427 --> 30:04.428
‐ Good luck.

30:04.428 --> 30:06.596
<i>♪ ♪</i>

30:06.596 --> 30:08.807
<i>‐ Man, I'm back in Rock Hill,</i>
<i>South Carolina,</i>

30:08.807 --> 30:11.143
<i>in my business slash forge.</i>

30:11.143 --> 30:14.521
Super excited to get started
on this damn sword, man.

30:14.521 --> 30:15.772
<i>♪ ♪</i>

30:15.772 --> 30:17.607
<i>I want to jump on this guard.</i>

30:17.607 --> 30:19.276
<i>It's gonna be</i>
<i>the most complicated piece,</i>

30:19.276 --> 30:21.987
so I wanna go ahead,
tackle it first.

30:21.987 --> 30:24.656
<i>I'm gonna attempt</i>
<i>to make the entire thing</i>

30:24.656 --> 30:27.034
<i>out of this one piece</i>
<i>of brass.</i>

30:27.034 --> 30:29.828
And so now we've got
the basic shape.

30:29.828 --> 30:33.790
We're gonna start removing
all this material out of here

30:33.790 --> 30:38.170
<i>and give us a place</i>
<i>for our tang to seat in.</i>

30:38.170 --> 30:39.796
After we get
all this milled out,

30:39.796 --> 30:42.799
you can see where the langets
are starting to form.

30:42.799 --> 30:44.676
Then we'll just dress those up.

30:44.676 --> 30:46.011
<i>Feeling really good</i>
<i>about today.</i>

30:46.011 --> 30:47.220
<i>I got a lot done.</i>

30:47.220 --> 30:49.806
<i>I'm actually itching</i>
<i>to do some forging.</i>

30:49.806 --> 30:52.184
<i>♪ ♪</i>

30:52.184 --> 30:53.685
<i>‐ So, it's day one.</i>

30:53.685 --> 30:55.854
<i>I'm back at my home forge</i>
<i>in Springfield, Virginia.</i>

30:55.854 --> 30:58.356
So, I think the more
difficult aspects of the build

30:58.356 --> 31:00.817
are the parameters
that I have to build it to.

31:00.817 --> 31:02.652
<i>It's very specific</i>
<i>and very tight,</i>

31:02.652 --> 31:05.072
<i>so we'll see what happens.</i>

31:05.072 --> 31:06.865
Because the parameters
are so tight

31:06.865 --> 31:08.366
<i>on the bend of the blade,</i>

31:08.366 --> 31:11.286
<i>my crazy idea</i>
<i>is to take a 6x6 log</i>

31:11.286 --> 31:13.789
<i>and then I'm gonna remove</i>
<i>all the excess wood</i>

31:13.789 --> 31:16.875
<i>and it's gonna leave me with</i>
<i>the blade shape that I want.</i>

31:16.875 --> 31:19.711
Wow, that went better
than I thought.

31:19.711 --> 31:23.715
I plan on heating up the metal
and whacking it on this log,

31:23.715 --> 31:26.009
and it's gonna bend
and conform to it.

31:26.009 --> 31:27.719
<i>♪ ♪</i>

31:27.719 --> 31:30.472
<i>I've seen a lot of the smiths</i>
<i>straighten out their blade</i>

31:30.472 --> 31:32.224
with a slap on the anvil,

31:32.224 --> 31:35.227
<i>so why not try to do it</i>
<i>on a big old log</i>

31:35.227 --> 31:36.895
<i>and put an arch in it.</i>

31:36.895 --> 31:38.897
<i>It seemed to work pretty well.</i>

31:38.897 --> 31:41.525
I, like, just jumped four hours
ahead of my little schedule.

31:41.525 --> 31:42.734
<i>♪ ♪</i>

31:42.734 --> 31:44.111
<i>I'm getting ready</i>
<i>to heat treat it.</i>

31:44.111 --> 31:45.403
<i>I wanna keep it thick,</i>

31:45.403 --> 31:47.572
<i>because I'm worried</i>
<i>about a warp.</i>

31:47.572 --> 31:48.907
Quenching.

31:48.907 --> 31:53.870
<i>♪ ♪</i>

31:53.870 --> 31:55.247
I am exhausted.

31:55.247 --> 31:57.207
<i>The quench went great.</i>

31:57.207 --> 31:58.875
<i>I'm ready to hit the rack.</i>

31:58.875 --> 32:01.086
<i>♪ ♪</i>

32:01.086 --> 32:02.546
<i>‐ All right, so it's day two,</i>

32:02.546 --> 32:04.589
getting ready to jump
right into some forging.

32:04.589 --> 32:06.466
Hammer time.

32:06.466 --> 32:09.427
<i>Well this is a very thin,</i>
<i>long blade.</i>

32:09.427 --> 32:11.805
<i>So what's difficult</i>
<i>about a thin and long blade</i>

32:11.805 --> 32:14.599
is just the pure fact
that it's gonna warp.

32:14.599 --> 32:17.477
<i>I'm constantly having to</i>
<i>hammer the big curves back out</i>

32:17.477 --> 32:19.396
<i>and try to keep it</i>
<i>straight as possible,</i>

32:19.396 --> 32:21.022
all while trying to draw it out

32:21.022 --> 32:22.899
and get the width
and the thickness I want.

32:22.899 --> 32:23.942
<i>♪ ♪</i>

32:23.942 --> 32:25.610
<i>It finally meets parameters.</i>

32:25.610 --> 32:28.530
<i>I'm finally able</i>
<i>to move on to quenching.</i>

32:28.530 --> 32:31.199
If I was to pick up a crack,
that's start over time.

32:31.199 --> 32:34.452
Man, this thing could do
anything in the quench here.

32:34.452 --> 32:36.621
<i>If this thing snaps,</i>

32:36.621 --> 32:37.873
<i>we're gonna be close</i>
<i>to being screwed, man.</i>

32:41.126 --> 32:43.336
<i>♪ ♪</i>

32:43.336 --> 32:45.005
I don't see any warps.

32:45.005 --> 32:48.300
It looks like
it's pretty straight.

32:48.300 --> 32:50.135
Super stoked about that.

32:50.135 --> 32:53.722
<i>After today,</i>
<i>I feel pretty damn awesome.</i>

32:53.722 --> 32:56.308
<i>[rock music]</i>

32:56.308 --> 32:58.185
<i>‐ Day three,</i>
<i>and I'm ready to get going</i>

32:58.185 --> 33:00.478
on sand‐casting the guard
for my Mameluke sword.

33:00.478 --> 33:01.521
<i>♪ ♪</i>

33:01.521 --> 33:03.857
<i>Never done</i>
<i>any sand casting before.</i>

33:03.857 --> 33:05.442
Go big or go home.

33:05.442 --> 33:07.694
<i>The consistency of the sand</i>
<i>is the big thing.</i>

33:07.694 --> 33:09.404
<i>I went with play box sand,</i>

33:09.404 --> 33:11.990
<i>mix it with some kitty litter,</i>
<i>and some water.</i>

33:11.990 --> 33:13.450
<i>Got it</i>
<i>to the right consistency</i>

33:13.450 --> 33:15.160
<i>and took a shot at it.</i>

33:15.160 --> 33:16.828
<i>♪ ♪</i>

33:16.828 --> 33:20.040
<i>I molded some clay</i>
<i>in the rough shape of a guard,</i>

33:20.040 --> 33:22.334
<i>and I used that</i>
<i>to mold the sand around.</i>

33:22.334 --> 33:23.668
<i>I pulled out the clay,</i>

33:23.668 --> 33:25.545
now I'm ready
to heat up my brass.

33:25.545 --> 33:27.130
Let's go cast some metal.

33:27.130 --> 33:28.423
<i>♪ ♪</i>

33:28.423 --> 33:29.716
<i>My mold is ready,</i>

33:29.716 --> 33:33.011
<i>my brass is a big pool</i>
<i>of molten hot brass.</i>

33:33.011 --> 33:35.513
I'm ready to pour it in,
so I'm gonna go for it.

33:35.513 --> 33:37.724
<i>I'm really hoping</i>
<i>this sand cast goes well,</i>

33:37.724 --> 33:40.143
<i>because I've used</i>
<i>a lot of time,</i>

33:40.143 --> 33:41.186
and if it doesn't,

33:41.186 --> 33:43.521
I don't know
how I'm gonna recover.

33:43.521 --> 33:45.315
Moment of truth, coming up.

33:45.315 --> 33:48.777
<i>♪ ♪</i>

33:48.777 --> 33:51.196
Holy cow, it worked!
I can't believe it.

33:51.196 --> 33:52.530
<i>I just gotta knock</i>
<i>the sand off,</i>

33:52.530 --> 33:54.157
<i>clean it up a little bit</i>
<i>on the grinder.</i>

33:54.157 --> 33:55.325
<i>♪ ♪</i>

33:55.325 --> 33:56.451
That's a guard.

33:56.451 --> 33:57.827
We got a guard!
[laughs]

33:57.827 --> 34:00.705
<i>♪ ♪</i>

34:00.705 --> 34:02.249
<i>‐ Day four, man.</i>
[blows]

34:02.249 --> 34:04.918
<i>Today, I've got</i>
<i>to sharpen this blade,</i>

34:04.918 --> 34:06.753
get it out of here.

34:06.753 --> 34:09.965
<i>My Ka‐Bar didn't do so well</i>
<i>in the rope cutting test,</i>

34:09.965 --> 34:12.259
<i>so I want this blade</i>
<i>to cut through</i>

34:12.259 --> 34:14.803
<i>whatever those guys are gonna</i>
<i>put this thing through.</i>

34:14.803 --> 34:17.555
<i>I want that Marine Corps anvil</i>
<i>pretty damn bad,</i>

34:17.555 --> 34:20.058
just because I want to be able
to represent the marines

34:20.058 --> 34:21.476
<i>in the Battle of the Branches.</i>

34:21.476 --> 34:23.561
<i>I believe I can come home</i>
<i>with that 50 grand</i>

34:23.561 --> 34:25.272
and represent
the Marine Corps very well.

34:25.272 --> 34:30.402
<i>♪ ♪</i>

34:30.402 --> 34:31.403
Damn!

34:31.403 --> 34:32.445
<i>♪ ♪</i>

34:32.445 --> 34:34.906
‐ [laughs]

34:34.906 --> 34:36.741
<i>♪ ♪</i>

34:36.741 --> 34:38.493
‐ So this is the start
of day four.

34:38.493 --> 34:39.995
<i>So today, I gotta start out</i>

34:39.995 --> 34:41.913
<i>with getting it</i>
<i>all fit together.</i>

34:41.913 --> 34:43.123
<i>♪ ♪</i>

34:43.123 --> 34:45.417
<i>When Doug Marcaida</i>
<i>swings this thing,</i>

34:45.417 --> 34:48.420
<i>it is going to slice</i>
<i>whatever it goes into.</i>

34:48.420 --> 34:49.671
<i>♪ ♪</i>

34:49.671 --> 34:51.423
<i>I realize I had</i>
<i>a little bit more time left</i>

34:51.423 --> 34:53.633
<i>and I wanted to try to put</i>
<i>the names of my competitors</i>

34:53.633 --> 34:56.011
<i>on the blade</i>
<i>with some gun glue.</i>

34:56.011 --> 34:58.179
Rick, Garrett, Tripp, and Gene.

34:58.179 --> 35:00.140
I'm pretty happy with it,
I know it's gonna cut.

35:00.140 --> 35:01.683
I am done!

35:01.683 --> 35:04.644
<i>[dramatic music]</i>

35:04.644 --> 35:08.231
<i>♪ ♪</i>

35:08.231 --> 35:09.399
[light laughter]

35:09.399 --> 35:11.693
‐ Looks like a fox
is attacking your skull.

35:11.693 --> 35:13.486
‐ Keeping me warm.
No?

35:13.486 --> 35:16.364
‐ All right, gentlemen.
Welcome back to The Forge.

35:16.364 --> 35:18.867
You marines have had four days
at your home forges

35:18.867 --> 35:21.953
to work on your Marine Corps
Mameluke swords.

35:21.953 --> 35:23.371
Tripp, how'd it go for you?

35:23.371 --> 35:25.582
‐ Man, it was
super challenging.

35:25.582 --> 35:27.667
<i>Ended up making it</i>
<i>out of 1085 steel</i>

35:27.667 --> 35:31.546
<i>with some brass</i>
<i>for the guard and the handle.</i>

35:31.546 --> 35:33.840
‐ Gene, how'd it go for you?
‐ It went fairly well,

35:33.840 --> 35:35.634
<i>I made it out of 1075 steel</i>

35:35.634 --> 35:39.596
<i>and the brass guard pushed me</i>
<i>beyond my limits.</i>

35:39.596 --> 35:41.389
‐ Here's what's
on the line, gents:

35:41.389 --> 35:43.516
a spot
at the Marine Corps anvil

35:43.516 --> 35:45.977
in our Battle of the Branches
final competition.

35:45.977 --> 35:47.479
That will be your opportunity

35:47.479 --> 35:49.773
to bring the title
of "Forged in Fire" champion

35:49.773 --> 35:51.191
back to the Marine Corps,

35:51.191 --> 35:54.778
and earn a check for $50,000.
‐ Oorah.

35:54.778 --> 35:56.196
‐ Well now it's time
for your weapons

35:56.196 --> 35:58.114
to go through a series
of three tests:

35:58.114 --> 35:59.908
a strength test,
a sharpness test,

35:59.908 --> 36:02.786
up first is the KEAL test.
Doug?

36:02.786 --> 36:06.623
<i>♪ ♪</i>

36:06.623 --> 36:09.417
‐ All right, marines,
welcome to the KEAL test.

36:09.417 --> 36:10.835
<i>[gunshot]</i>

36:10.835 --> 36:12.921
To find out what lethal damage
your weapon will do,

36:12.921 --> 36:14.214
I will take your weapon,

36:14.214 --> 36:16.174
deliver killing blows
to this ballistics dummy.

36:16.174 --> 36:17.592
Tripp, you're up first.
You ready for this?

36:17.592 --> 36:19.177
‐ Get it, killer.
‐ Oorah.

36:19.177 --> 36:20.512
[laughs]

36:20.512 --> 36:21.763
<i>♪ ♪</i>

36:21.763 --> 36:24.182
‐ Going into this KEAL test,
man, I just hope

36:24.182 --> 36:26.685
that it performs better
than the Ka‐Bar that I made.

36:26.685 --> 36:29.020
<i>♪ ♪</i>

36:29.020 --> 36:32.023
<i>[rock music]</i>

36:32.023 --> 36:39.030
<i>♪ ♪</i>

36:41.282 --> 36:42.701
Yikes!

36:42.701 --> 36:49.708
<i>♪ ♪</i>

36:51.543 --> 36:54.212
‐ Whoa!
‐ Oh!

36:54.212 --> 36:56.214
‐ Holy moly!
‐ [laughs]

36:56.214 --> 36:59.884
<i>[dramatic music]</i>

36:59.884 --> 37:02.804
‐ All right, Tripp, first up,
the handle construction.

37:02.804 --> 37:04.264
It is comfortable.

37:04.264 --> 37:07.225
Your edge here is sharp,

37:07.225 --> 37:09.310
even cutting through the skull,
no issues at all.

37:09.310 --> 37:12.564
No chipping, no glinting.
And when you thrust with this,

37:12.564 --> 37:14.899
it penetrates and cuts
all the way out.

37:14.899 --> 37:18.486
Overall, sir,
your weapon will KEAL.

37:18.486 --> 37:19.904
‐ All right, oorah.

37:19.904 --> 37:21.656
‐ All right, Gene, you're next.
You ready?

37:21.656 --> 37:23.241
‐ Let's do this.
‐ Let's do this.

37:23.241 --> 37:24.617
<i>♪ ♪</i>

37:24.617 --> 37:26.578
‐ [chuckles] Oh, yeah.
<i>‐ I'm pretty darn nervous.</i>

37:26.578 --> 37:28.121
<i>I know my blade is sharp,</i>
<i>but I don't know</i>

37:28.121 --> 37:29.998
<i>if it's strong enough</i>
<i>to get through these tests.</i>

37:29.998 --> 37:31.583
<i>I'm really worried that</i>
<i>at the end of this test,</i>

37:31.583 --> 37:33.209
my sword's gonna
look like a pretzel.

37:33.209 --> 37:34.919
<i>♪ ♪</i>

37:34.919 --> 37:37.922
<i>[rock music]</i>

37:37.922 --> 37:44.929
<i>♪ ♪</i>

37:57.358 --> 38:00.320
<i>[dramatic music]</i>

38:00.320 --> 38:02.030
<i>♪ ♪</i>

38:02.030 --> 38:03.740
Oh, no.
It bent it.

38:03.740 --> 38:06.785
<i>♪ ♪</i>

38:06.785 --> 38:08.328
‐ All right, Gene.

38:08.328 --> 38:10.622
Your weapon picked up a warp
right here.

38:10.622 --> 38:11.790
‐ Yes.
‐ 'Kay?

38:11.790 --> 38:13.792
Your handle,
coupled with blood all over,

38:13.792 --> 38:16.294
made it very slippery
and hard to hold onto

38:16.294 --> 38:18.463
'cause it's blocky and smooth,

38:18.463 --> 38:20.882
and I lost my grip on it.

38:20.882 --> 38:22.509
That's a very dangerous thing
to happen

38:22.509 --> 38:23.968
when you're trying
to wield the weapon.

38:23.968 --> 38:26.387
But your edge is still sharp,

38:26.387 --> 38:28.681
your tip is still thrustable,

38:28.681 --> 38:31.518
and more importantly,
it will KEAL.

38:31.518 --> 38:34.813
‐ [laughing]
That'll work.

38:34.813 --> 38:37.982
<i>♪ ♪</i>

38:37.982 --> 38:40.026
‐ All right, gentlemen,
it's time for the strength test.

38:40.026 --> 38:42.153
So, to test the overall
construction of your blade

38:42.153 --> 38:43.488
and see if they're gonna
hold an edge,

38:43.488 --> 38:45.031
I'll be smashing 'em
into these pots.

38:45.031 --> 38:46.491
<i>♪ ♪</i>

38:46.491 --> 38:48.117
Now remember,
this test is not about

38:48.117 --> 38:49.702
what your swords do
to those pots,

38:49.702 --> 38:51.663
but what those pots
do to your swords.

38:51.663 --> 38:53.164
Tripp, you're up, you ready?
‐ Ready.

38:53.164 --> 38:54.999
‐ Okay.

38:54.999 --> 38:57.168
<i>‐ These clay pots are thick,</i>
<i>they're brutal.</i>

38:57.168 --> 38:59.420
<i>I mean they'll send</i>
<i>a shock wave down this blade,</i>

38:59.420 --> 39:01.548
and there's no telling
what's gonna happen.

39:01.548 --> 39:08.596
<i>♪ ♪</i>

39:10.348 --> 39:12.058
‐ Oh, my gosh.
‐ Yup.

39:12.058 --> 39:13.726
Holy moly.

39:13.726 --> 39:17.313
[laughing]
God, no.

39:17.313 --> 39:20.608
<i>♪ ♪</i>

39:20.608 --> 39:24.028
‐ Well, Tripp, a few things
before we get to the obvious.

39:24.028 --> 39:26.531
Your handle construction,
very comfortable.

39:26.531 --> 39:27.699
Felt really good in my hand,

39:27.699 --> 39:29.242
felt like I could do
a lot with it.

39:29.242 --> 39:32.203
But right there at the edge,

39:32.203 --> 39:34.247
there's that little brown spot.

39:34.247 --> 39:35.707
You had a micro‐crack
on that edge.

39:35.707 --> 39:37.208
‐ Ohh, yep.

39:37.208 --> 39:39.502
‐ So as soon as I hit that pot,
it cut loose.

39:39.502 --> 39:41.796
I loved its feel, its shape,
and its look,

39:41.796 --> 39:43.548
but...obvious problem.

39:43.548 --> 39:46.134
<i>♪ ♪</i>

39:46.134 --> 39:47.760
‐ All right, Tripp.

39:47.760 --> 39:49.971
While I know any marine
could take that blade

39:49.971 --> 39:52.724
and still continue to fight,
in this competition,

39:52.724 --> 39:54.893
your blade suffered
a catastrophic failure

39:54.893 --> 39:56.728
after one strike on that vase.

39:56.728 --> 39:58.605
Gene, your blade
only has to survive

39:58.605 --> 40:00.565
one strike on these pots.

40:00.565 --> 40:03.109
<i>♪ ♪</i>

40:03.109 --> 40:04.819
<i>‐ The entire</i>
<i>marine championship</i>

40:04.819 --> 40:07.030
for "Forged in Fire"
lies on one swing,

40:07.030 --> 40:09.073
<i>and I've got a big old warp</i>
<i>in my blade,</i>

40:09.073 --> 40:10.783
so it's not over yet.

40:10.783 --> 40:14.078
<i>♪ ♪</i>

40:18.750 --> 40:24.047
<i>♪ ♪</i>

40:25.798 --> 40:27.675
‐ Nice job.

40:27.675 --> 40:30.595
<i>♪ ♪</i>

40:30.595 --> 40:33.097
‐ Gene, first off,
you're in one piece.

40:33.097 --> 40:35.600
You picked up
that bend earlier on,

40:35.600 --> 40:37.727
but you didn't pick up
any more in this test.

40:37.727 --> 40:39.812
Strong blade.
Held up. Good job.

40:39.812 --> 40:40.772
‐ Thank you.

40:40.772 --> 40:43.816
<i>♪ ♪</i>

40:43.816 --> 40:47.153
‐ All right, Tripp, looks like
Gene's blade held up.

40:47.153 --> 40:49.238
That means that
you cannot move forward

40:49.238 --> 40:51.824
to represent the Marine Corps
in our next challenge.

40:51.824 --> 40:53.159
Please leave The Forge.

40:53.159 --> 40:54.619
<i>‐ Super disappointed.</i>

40:54.619 --> 40:56.162
<i>There's really no way to tell</i>
that

40:56.162 --> 40:58.331
you have, like, any minor cracks
or anything like that,

40:58.331 --> 41:00.625
so you just‐‐hey,
you find out when you test 'em.

41:00.625 --> 41:02.961
<i>That's how we found out today.</i>
Get it, brother.

41:02.961 --> 41:04.712
<i>Gene's gonna freakin'</i>
<i>bring home</i>

41:04.712 --> 41:07.298
<i>that Battle of the Branches</i>
<i>Marine Corps anvil,</i>

41:07.298 --> 41:08.967
and he's winning it
for the Marine Corps.

41:08.967 --> 41:12.178
<i>♪ ♪</i>

41:12.178 --> 41:15.098
‐ Gene, congratulations.
You've won this competition,

41:15.098 --> 41:17.183
and that means that
you're gonna be moving forward

41:17.183 --> 41:20.311
into our Battle of the Branches
final competition

41:20.311 --> 41:23.022
<i>to represent the Marine Corps</i>
<i>at the Marine Corps' anvil.</i>

41:23.022 --> 41:24.732
And that's gonna give you
an opportunity

41:24.732 --> 41:26.943
to win a check for $50,000.

41:26.943 --> 41:28.486
Good job, brother.
‐ Thank you.

41:28.486 --> 41:29.904
[applause]

41:29.904 --> 41:32.198
<i>‐ Holy cow.</i>
<i>I did not see this coming,</i>

41:32.198 --> 41:34.325
<i>it's been a fun ride</i>
<i>up until now,</i>

41:34.325 --> 41:36.327
but now I gotta represent
the marines.

41:36.327 --> 41:39.163
So now, it's game on
and it's about to get real.

41:39.163 --> 41:41.541
<i>And those other branch service</i>
<i>members better look out.</i>

41:41.541 --> 41:42.917
[shouts]

41:42.917 --> 41:48.214
<i>♪ ♪</i>
